{"questionId":"25681","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following diagram shows part of the graph of a quadratic function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math>.</p>\n<p>The graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> has its vertex at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>)</mo></math>, and it passes through point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Q</mtext></math> as shown.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/bb9b6d38abbe948917fcba47938cccb8f876b389.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The line <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math> is tangent to the graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Q</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Now consider another function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math>. The derivative of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> is given by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>′</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>d</mi></math>,&nbsp;where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi></math> for which <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> is an increasing function.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p>Recognizing that for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> to be increasing,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mi>d</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, or&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p>The vertex must be above the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>d</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>d</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(R1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p>attempting to find discriminant of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>'</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>22</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>d</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>recognizing discriminant must be negative&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(R1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>32</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>d</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Δ</mtext><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"25681","referenceCode":"22M.1.SL.TZ2.7d","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the values of d for which g is an increasing function.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.2—Increasing and decreasing functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.3—Differentiating polynomials, n E Z","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.11—Transformation of functions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}